.TH F00-DATE 1 "2026" "f00 0.15.1" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
f00\-date \- print or set the system date and time (f00tils)
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B f00\-date
[\fIOPTION\fR]... [\fI+FORMAT\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
Display the current time in the given FORMAT, or set the system date.
Pure assembly multicall. MIT.
.PP
Default is modern mode.
.B \-\-core
selects strict GNU date\-compatible output.
.SH COREUTILS FLAGS
.TP
\fB\-u\fR, \fB\-\-utc\fR, \fB\-\-universal\fR
print or set Coordinated Universal Time (UTC)
.TP
\fB\-\-iso\-8601\fR[=\fITIMESPEC\fR]
output date/time in ISO 8601 format
.TP
\fB\-d\fR, \fB\-\-date\fR=\fISTRING\fR
display time described by STRING (when supported)
.PP
See
.B f00\-date \-\-help
for the full flag list.
.SH MODERN FLAGS
.TP
\fB\-\-core\fR
strict coreutils\-compatible output
.TP
\fB\-j\fR, \fB\-\-json\fR
JSON timestamp summary
.TP
\fB\-\-csv\fR
CSV timestamp summary
.SH AUTHOR
f00 contributors. License MIT.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR date (1),
.BR f00 (1)
.PP
https://f00.sh
